# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-husbandry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne was the father of bookseller Christopher Robin Milne, upon whom the character Christopher Robin is based.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] It was during a visit to London Zoo, where Christopher became enamoured of the tame and amiable bear Winnipeg, that Milne was inspired to write the story of Winnie-the-Pooh for his son.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne bequeathed the original manuscripts of the Winnie-the-Pooh stories to the Wren Library at Trinity College, Cambridge, his alma mater.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Alan Alexander Milne was born in Kilburn, London, to John Vine Milne, who was born in Jamaica, and Sarah Marie Milne (née Heginbotham), on 18 January 1882.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He grew up at Henley House School, 6/7 Mortimer Road (now Crescent), Kilburn, a small independent school run by his father.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He taught himself to read at the age of two.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne attended Westminster School and Trinity College, Cambridge, where he studied on a mathematics scholarship, graduating with a Bachelor of Arts in Mathematics in 1903, though he was always interested in writing.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He edited and wrote for *Granta*, a student magazine.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He collaborated with his brother Kenneth and their articles appeared over the initials AKM.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne's work came to the attention of the leading British humour magazine *Punch*, where Milne was to become a contributor and later an assistant editor.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Considered a talented cricket fielder, Milne played for two amateur teams that were largely composed of British writers: the Allahakbarries and the Authors XI.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] His teammates included fellow writers J.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne joined the British Army during World War I and served as an officer in the Royal Warwickshire Regiment.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He was commissioned into the 4th Battalion, Royal Warwickshire Regiment, on 1 February 1915 as a second lieutenant (on probation).
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] His commission was confirmed on 20 December 1915.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He served on the Somme as a signals officer from July–November 1916, but caught trench fever and was invalided back to England.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Having recuperated, he worked as a signals instructor, before being recruited into military intelligence to write propaganda articles for MI7 (b) between 1917 and 1918.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He was discharged on 14 February 1919, and settled in Mallord Street, Chelsea.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He relinquished his commission on 19 February 1920, retaining the rank of lieutenant.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] After the war, he wrote a denunciation of war titled *Peace with Honour* (1934), which he retracted somewhat with 1940's *War with Honour*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] During World War II, Milne was one of the most prominent critics of fellow English writer (and Authors XI cricket teammate) P.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Wodehouse, who was captured at his country home in France by the Nazis and imprisoned for a year.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Wodehouse made radio broadcasts about his internment, which were broadcast from Berlin.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Although the light-hearted broadcasts made fun of the Germans, Milne accused Wodehouse of committing an act of near treason by cooperating with his country's enemy.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Wodehouse got some revenge on his former friend (e.g. in *The Mating Season*) by creating fatuous parodies of the Christopher Robin poems in some of his later stories, and claiming that Milne "was probably jealous of all other writers....
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne married Dorothy "Daphne" de Sélincourt (1890–1971) in 1913 and their son Christopher Robin Milne was born in 1920.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 1925, Milne bought a country home, Cotchford Farm, in Hartfield, East Sussex.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] During World War II, Milne was a captain in the British Home Guard in Hartfield & Forest Row, insisting on being plain "Mr.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He retired to the farm after a stroke and brain surgery in 1952 left him an invalid; and by August 1953, "he seemed very old and disenchanted." Milne died in January 1956, aged 74.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] After graduating from Cambridge University in 1903, A.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne contributed humorous verse and whimsical essays to *Punch*, joining the staff in 1906 and becoming an assistant editor.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] During this period he published 18 plays and three novels, including the murder mystery *The Red House Mystery* (1922).
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] His son was born in August 1920 and in 1924 Milne produced a collection of children's poems, *When We Were Very Young*, which were illustrated by *Punch* staff cartoonist E.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] A collection of short stories for children *A Gallery of Children*, and other stories that became part of the Winnie-the-Pooh books, were first published in 1925.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne was an early screenwriter for the nascent British film industry, writing four stories filmed in 1920 for the company Minerva Films (founded in 1920 by the actor Leslie Howard and his friend and story editor Adrian Brunel).
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] These were *The Bump*, starring Aubrey Smith; *Twice Two*; *Five Pound Reward*; and *Bookworms*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Some of these films survive in the archives of the British Film Institute.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne had met Howard when the actor starred in Milne's play *Mr Pim Passes By* in London.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne is most famous for his two *Pooh* books about a boy named Christopher Robin after his son, Christopher Robin Milne (1920–1996), and various characters inspired by his son's stuffed animals, most notably the bear named Winnie-the-Pooh.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Christopher Robin Milne's stuffed bear, originally named Edward, was renamed Winnie after a Canadian black bear named Winnie (after Winnipeg), which was used as a military mascot in World War I, and left to London Zoo during the war.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] "The Pooh" comes from a swan the young Milne named "Pooh".
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Shepard illustrated the original Pooh books, using his own son's teddy Growler ("a magnificent bear") as the model.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The rest of Christopher Robin Milne's toys, Piglet, Eeyore, Kanga, Roo and Tigger, were incorporated into A.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne's stories, and two more characters – Rabbit and Owl – were created by Milne's imagination.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Christopher Robin Milne's own toys are now on display in New York where 750,000 people visit them every year.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The fictional Hundred Acre Wood of the Pooh stories derives from Five Hundred Acre Wood in Ashdown Forest in East Sussex, South East England, where the Pooh stories were set.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Shepard drew on the landscapes of Ashdown Forest as inspiration for many of the illustrations he provided for the Pooh books.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Not yet known as Pooh, he made his first appearance in a poem, "Teddy Bear", published in *Punch* magazine in February 1924 and republished that year in *When We Were Very Young*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Pooh first appeared in the *London Evening News* on Christmas Eve, 1925, in a story called "The Wrong Sort of Bees".
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] *Winnie-the-Pooh* was published in 1926, followed by *The House at Pooh Corner* in 1928.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] A second collection of nursery rhymes, *Now We Are Six*, was published in 1927.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne also published four plays in this period.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He also "gallantly stepped forward" to contribute a quarter of the costs of dramatising P.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] *The World of Pooh* won the Lewis Carroll Shelf Award in 1958.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] But once Milne had, in his own words, "said goodbye to all that in 70,000 words" (the approximate length of his four principal children's books), he had no intention of producing any reworkings lacking in originality, given that one of the sources of inspiration, his son, was growing older.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Another reason Milne stopped writing children's books, and especially about Winnie-the-Pooh, was that he felt "amazement and disgust" over the immense fame his son was exposed to, and said that "I feel that the legal Christopher Robin has already had more publicity than I want for him.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In his literary home, *Punch*, where the *When We Were Very Young* verses first appeared, Methuen continued to publish whatever Milne wrote, including the long poem "The Norman Church" and an assembly of articles entitled *Year In, Year Out* (which Milne likened to a benefit night for the author).
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 1929, Milne adapted Kenneth Grahame's novel *The Wind in the Willows* for the stage as *Toad of Toad Hall*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The title was an implicit admission that such chapters as Chapter 7, "The Piper at the Gates of Dawn," could not survive translation to the theatre.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] A special introduction written by Milne is included in some editions of Grahame's novel.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] It was first performed at the Playhouse Theatre, Liverpool, on 21 December 1929 before it made its West End debut the following year at the Lyric Theatre on 17 December 1930.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The play was revived in the West End from 1931 to 1935, and since the 1960s there have been West End revivals during the Christmas season; actors who have performed in the play include Judi Dench and Ian McKellen.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne and his wife became estranged from their son, who came to resent what he saw as his father's exploitation of his childhood and came to hate the books that had thrust him into the public eye.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Christopher's marriage to his first cousin, Lesley de Sélincourt, distanced him still further from his parents – Lesley's father and Christopher's mother had not spoken to each other for 30 years.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne died at his home in Hartfield, Sussex, on 31 January 1956, 13 days after his 74th birthday.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] A memorial service took place on 10 February at All Hallows-by-the-Tower church in London.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne's Pooh books were left to four beneficiaries: his family, the Royal Literary Fund, Westminster School and the Garrick Club.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] After Milne's death in 1956, his widow sold her rights to the Pooh characters to Stephen Slesinger, whose widow sold the rights after Slesinger's death to Walt Disney Productions, which has made many Pooh cartoon movies, a Disney Channel television show, as well as Pooh-related merchandise.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 2001, the other beneficiaries sold their interest in the estate to the Disney Corporation for $350m.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Previously Disney had been paying twice-yearly royalties to these beneficiaries.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Shepard also received a sum in the deal.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The UK copyright on the text of the original Winnie the Pooh books expires on 1 January 2027; at the beginning of the year after the 70th anniversary of the author's death (PMA-70), and has already expired in those countries with a PMA-60 rule.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] This applies to all of Milne's works except those first published posthumously.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The illustrations in the Pooh books will remain under copyright until the same amount of time after the illustrator's death has passed; in the UK, this will be 1 January 2047.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In the US, copyright on the four children's books (including the illustrations) expired 95 years after publication of each of the books.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Specifically: copyright on the book *When We Were Very Young* expired in 2020; copyright on the book *Winnie-the-Pooh* expired in 2022; copyright on the book *Now We Are Six* expired in 2023; and copyright on the book *The House at Pooh Corner* expired in 2024.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 2008, a collection of original illustrations featuring Winnie-the-Pooh and his animal friends sold for more than £1.2 million at auction at Sotheby's, London.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] *Forbes* magazine ranked Winnie the Pooh the most valuable fictional character in 2002; Winnie the Pooh merchandising products alone had annual sales of more than $5.9 billion.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 2005, Winnie the Pooh generated $6 billion, a figure surpassed only by Mickey Mouse.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] A memorial plaque in Ashdown Forest, unveiled by Christopher Robin in 1979, commemorates the work of A.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne and Shepard in creating the world of Pooh.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The inscription states they "captured the magic of Ashdown Forest, and gave it to the world".
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 2003, *Winnie-the-Pooh* was ranked number 7 on the BBC's The Big Read poll which determined the UK's "best-loved novels".
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In 2006, Winnie-the-Pooh received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame, marking the 80th birthday of Milne's creation.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Marking the 90th anniversary of Milne's creation of the character, and the 90th birthday of Queen Elizabeth II, *Winnie-the-Pooh Meets the Queen* (2016) sees Pooh meet the Queen at Buckingham Palace.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The illustrated and audio adventure is narrated by the actor Jim Broadbent.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Also in 2016, a new character, a Penguin, was unveiled in *The Best Bear in All the World*, which was inspired by a long-lost photograph of Milne and his son Christopher with a toy penguin.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] An exhibition entitled *Winnie-the-Pooh: Exploring a Classic* appeared at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London from 9 December 2017 to 8 April 2018.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The composer Harold Fraser-Simson, a near neighbour, produced six books of Milne songs between 1924 and 1932.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The poems have been parodied many times, including in the books *When We Were Rather Older* and *Now We Are Sixty*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The 1963 film *The King's Breakfast* was based on Milne's poem of the same name.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne has been portrayed in television and film.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Domhnall Gleeson plays him in *Goodbye Christopher Robin*, a 2017 biographical drama film.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] In the 2018 fantasy film *Christopher Robin*, an extension of the Disney Winnie the Pooh franchise, Tristan Sturrock plays Milne, and filming took place at Ashdown Forest.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] An elementary school in Houston, Texas, operated by the Houston Independent School District (HISD), is named after Milne.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne Elementary School in Brays Oaks, opened in 1991.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The original manuscripts for *Winnie-the-Pooh* and *The House at Pooh Corner* are archived at Trinity College Library, Cambridge.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne's papers are housed at the Harry Ransom Center at the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The collection, established at the centre in 1964, consists of manuscript drafts and fragments for over 150 of Milne's works, as well as correspondence, legal documents, genealogical records, and some personal effects.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The library division holds several books formerly belonging to Milne and his wife Dorothy.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] The center also has small collections of correspondence from Christopher Robin Milne and Milne's frequent illustrator E.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] Milne did not speak out much on the subject of religion, although he used religious terms to explain his decision, while remaining a pacifist, to join the British Home Guard.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-a-milne] He wrote: "In fighting Hitler we are truly fighting the Devil, the Anti-Christ ...
[src:animal-husbandry/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The book was reviewed in contemporary periodicals including the *London Medical Gazette*, *The Athenaeum*, and *The Veterinary Record*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] It was later noted by writers including Henry S.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Ralph Fletcher (1780—1851) was a surgeon based in Gloucester.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London and received an M.D. from the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He held appointments at the Gloucester Infirmary, Dispensary, and Lunatic Asylum.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He published medical papers on the relation between mental and physical health.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher was twice elected Mayor of Gloucester and served as president of the local branch of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He lived on Barton Street, near the city's animal pound, and his observations of the animals kept there were said to have inspired *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In a brief "Preliminary Note", Fletcher writes about the suffering of animals, especially those dependent on humans.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He rejects the view that animals are insensible to pain or that their suffering is divinely ordained, and argues for compassion on moral and theological grounds.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In "Importance of the Subject", Fletcher draws on his experience as president of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes that public acts of cruelty form only a small part of a wider problem, and that abuse often takes place in private spaces such as stables, slaughterhouses, and homes.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He argues that existing legislation was inadequate, because small fines and judicial discretion to reduce sentences did not deter offenders.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The main part of the book consists of notes on individual animals and practices.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher describes donkeys as animals commonly subjected to overwork and neglect.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He condemns blood sports such as shooting tied cocks and badger-baiting.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] His discussion of cats and dogs contrasts their treatment: he writes that cats were often tormented or killed for amusement, while dogs suffered from starvation, beatings, cart-work, and fighting.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher criticises methods used in the rearing and slaughter of calves and lambs, including starvation and repeated bleeding to produce white veal.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes about overwork, neglect, and abandonment, and argues that owners as well as drivers should be held legally responsible.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher ends by calling for tougher penalties for cruelty, official oversight of slaughterhouses and stables, wider public instruction in humane treatment, and hospitals for sick and injured animals.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] A review in the *London Medical Gazette* described the book as the work of a hospital surgeon acquainted with suffering.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The reviewer agreed with Fletcher's criticism of animal experimentation, but called his proposal for hospitals for animals a "somewhat Utopian scheme" said to have some precedent in the East.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Salt in the "Bibliography of Animal Rights" section of his 1892 work *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*, where he referred to it as a treatise on animal cruelty.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In his 1989 reference work *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*, Charles R.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Magel described *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals* as an early account of animal abuse in the Gloucester area and noted its proposal for hospitals for animals modelled on human institutions.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-husbandry/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-husbandry/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-husbandry/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] A wide range of other species, such as horse, water buffalo, llama, rabbit, and guinea pig, are used as livestock in some parts of the world.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Insect farming, as well as aquaculture of fish, molluscs, and crustaceans, is widespread.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Modern animal husbandry relies on production systems adapted to the available land.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Subsistence farming is being superseded by intensive animal farming in the more developed parts of the world, where, for example, beef cattle are kept in high-density feedlots, and thousands of chickens may be raised in broiler houses or batteries.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] On poorer soil, such as in uplands, animals are often kept more extensively and may be allowed to roam widely, foraging for themselves.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animal agriculture at modern scale drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Most livestock are herbivores, except (among the most commonly-kept species) for pigs and chickens, which are omnivores.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Ruminants like cattle and sheep are adapted to feed on grass; they can forage outdoors or may be fed entirely or in part on rations richer in energy and protein, such as pelleted cereals.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Pigs and poultry cannot digest the cellulose in forage and require other high-protein foods.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Farmers and ranchers who raise livestock are considered to practice *animal husbandry*.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The domestication of livestock was driven by the need to have food on hand when hunting was unproductive.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The desirable characteristics of a domestic animal are that it should be useful to the domesticator, should be able to thrive in their company, should breed freely, and be easy to tend.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Domestication was not a single event, but a process repeated at various periods in different places.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Sheep and goats were the animals that accompanied the nomads in the Middle East, while cattle and pigs were associated with more settled communities.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The first wild animal to be domesticated was the dog.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Half-wild dogs, perhaps starting with young individuals, may have been tolerated as scavengers and killers of vermin, and, being naturally pack hunters, were predisposed to become part of the human pack and join in the hunt.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Prey animals, sheep, goats, pigs, and cattle, were progressively domesticated early in the history of agriculture.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Pigs were domesticated in the Near East between 8,500 and 8000 BC, sheep and goats in or near the Fertile Crescent about 8,500 BC, and cattle from wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan around 8,500 BC.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] A cow was a great advantage to a villager as she produced more milk than her calf needed, and her strength could be put to use as a working animal, pulling a plough to increase production of crops, and drawing a sledge, and later a cart, to bring the produce home from the field.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Draught animals were first used about 4,000 BC in the Middle East, increasing agricultural production immeasurably.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In southern Asia, the elephant was domesticated by 6,000 BC.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Fossilised chicken bones dated to 5040 BC have been found in northeastern China, far from where their wild ancestors lived in the jungles of tropical Asia, but archaeologists believe that the original purpose of domestication was for the sport of cockfighting.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Meanwhile, in South America, the llama and the alpaca had been domesticated, probably before 3,000 BC, as beasts of burden and for their wool.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Neither was strong enough to pull a plough, which limited the development of agriculture in the New World.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Horses occur naturally on the steppes of Central Asia, and their domestication began around 3,000 BC in the Black Sea and Caspian Sea region.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Although horses were originally seen as a source of meat, their use as pack animals and for riding followed.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Around the same time, the wild ass was being tamed in Egypt.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Camels were domesticated soon after this, with the Bactrian camel in Mongolia and the Arabian camel becoming beasts of burden.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] By 1000 BC, caravans of Arabian camels were linking India with Mesopotamia and the Mediterranean.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In ancient Egypt, cattle were the most important livestock, and sheep, goats, and pigs were also kept; poultry including ducks, geese, and pigeons were captured in nets and bred on farms, where they were force-fed with dough to fatten them.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The Nile provided a plentiful source of fish.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Honey bees were domesticated from at least the Old Kingdom, providing both honey and wax.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In ancient Rome, all the livestock known in ancient Egypt were available.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In addition, rabbits were domesticated for food by the first century BC.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] To help flush them out from their burrows, the polecat was domesticated as the ferret, its use described by Pliny the Elder.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In northern Europe, agriculture, including animal husbandry, declined after the collapse of the Roman Empire.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Some aspects, such as the herding of animals, continued throughout the period.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] By the 11th century, the economy had recovered, and the countryside was again productive.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Woodland for [feeding] 70 pigs." The improvements of animal husbandry in the medieval period in Europe went hand in hand with other developments.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Improvements to the plough allowed the soil to be tilled to a greater depth.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Horses took over from oxen as the main providers of traction, new ideas on crop rotation were developed, and the growing of crops for winter fodder gained ground.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Peas, beans, and vetches became common; they increased soil fertility through nitrogen fixation, allowing more livestock to be kept.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The exploration and colonisation of North and South America resulted in the introduction of crops such as maize, potatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc into Europe.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] At the same time, the principal Old World livestock – cattle, horses, sheep, and goats – were introduced into the New World for the first time along with wheat, barley, rice, and turnips.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Selective breeding for desired traits was established as a scientific practice by Robert Bakewell during the British Agricultural Revolution in the 18th century.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] One of his most important breeding programs was with sheep.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Using native stock, he was able to quickly select for large, yet fine-boned sheep, with long, lustrous wool.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The Lincoln Longwool was improved by Bakewell, and, in turn, the Lincoln was used to develop the subsequent breed, the New (or Dishley) Leicester.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] It was hornless and had a square, meaty body with straight top lines.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] These sheep were exported widely and have contributed to numerous modern breeds.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Under his influence, English farmers began to breed cattle primarily for beef.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Long-horned heifers were crossed with the Westmoreland bull to create the Dishley Longhorn.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The semi-natural, unfertilised pastures formed by traditional agricultural methods in Europe were managed by grazing and mowing.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] As the ecological impact of this land management strategy is similar to that of natural disturbances such as grazing and wildfire, this agricultural system shares many beneficial characteristics with a natural habitat, including promoting biodiversity.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] This strategy is declining in Europe today due to intensified agriculture.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The mechanized and chemical methods used are causing biodiversity to decline.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Traditionally, animal husbandry was part of the subsistence farmer's way of life, producing not only the food needed by the family but also the fuel, fertiliser, clothing, transport, and draught power.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Killing the animal for food was a secondary consideration; wherever possible its products such as wool, eggs, milk and blood (by the Maasai) were harvested while the animal was still alive.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In the traditional system of transhumance, people and livestock moved seasonally between fixed summer and winter pastures; in montane regions the summer pasture was up in the mountains, the winter pasture in the valleys.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animals can be kept extensively or intensively.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Extensive systems involve animals roaming at will, or under the supervision of a herdsman, often for their protection from predators.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Ranching in the Western United States involves large herds of cattle grazing widely over public and private lands.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Similar cattle stations are found in South America, Australia, and other places with large areas of land and low rainfall.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Ranching systems have been used for sheep, deer, ostrich, emu, llama and alpaca.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In the uplands of the United Kingdom, sheep are turned out on the fells in spring and graze the abundant mountain grasses untended, being brought to lower altitudes late in the year, with supplementary feeding being provided in winter.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In rural locations, pigs and poultry can obtain much of their nutrition from scavenging, and in African communities, hens may live for months without being fed, and still produce one or two eggs a week.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In between these two extremes are semi-intensive, often family-run farms where livestock graze outside for much of the year, silage or hay is made to cover the times of year when the grass stops growing, and fertiliser, feed, and other inputs are brought onto the farm from outside.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animals used as livestock are predominantly herbivorous, the main exceptions being the pig and the chicken, which are omnivorous.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Herbivores can be divided into "concentrate selectors", which selectively feed on seeds, fruits, and highly nutritious young foliage; "grazers", which mainly feed on grass; and "intermediate feeders", which choose their diet from the full range of available plant material.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Cattle, sheep, goats, deer, and antelopes are ruminants; they digest food in two steps, chewing and swallowing in the normal way, and then regurgitating the semidigested cud to chew it again and thus extract the maximum possible food value.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The dietary needs of these animals are mostly met by eating grass.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Grasses grow from the base of the leaf-blade, enabling it to thrive even when heavily grazed or cut.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In many climates, grass growth is seasonal, for example, in the temperate summer or tropical rainy season, so some areas of the crop are set aside to be cut and preserved, either as hay (dried grass), or as silage (fermented grass).
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Other forage crops are also grown and many of these, as well as crop residues, can be ensiled to fill the gap in the nutritional needs of livestock in the lean season.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Extensively reared animals may subsist entirely on forage, but more intensively kept livestock will require energy and protein-rich foods in addition.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Energy is mainly derived from cereals and cereal by-products, fats and oils, and sugar-rich foods, while protein may come from fish or meat meal, milk products, legumes, and other plant foods, often the by-products of vegetable oil extraction.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Pigs and poultry are non-ruminants and are unable to digest the cellulose in grass and other forages, so they are fed entirely on cereals and other high-energy foodstuffs.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The ingredients for the animals' rations can be grown on the farm or bought as pelleted or cubed compound foodstuffs, specially formulated for different classes of livestock, their growth stages, and their specific nutritional requirements.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Vitamins and minerals are added to balance the diet.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Farmed fish are usually fed pelleted food.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The breeding of farm animals seldom occurs spontaneously but is managed by farmers to encourage traits considered desirable.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] These include hardiness, fertility, docility, mothering abilities, fast growth rates, low feed consumption per unit of growth, better body proportions, higher yields, and better fibre qualities.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Undesirable traits such as health defects and aggressiveness are selected against.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Selective breeding has been responsible for significant productivity increases.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] For example, in 2007, a typical broiler chicken at eight weeks old was 4.8 times as heavy as a bird of similar age in 1957, while in the thirty years to 2007, the average milk yield of a dairy cow in the United States nearly doubled.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Good husbandry, proper feeding, and hygiene are the main contributors to animal health on the farm, bringing economic benefits through maximised production.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] When, despite these precautions, animals still become sick, they are treated with veterinary medicines, by the farmer and the veterinarian.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In the European Union, when farmers treat their own animals, they are required to follow treatment guidelines and record the treatments given.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animals are susceptible to many diseases and conditions that may affect their health.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Some, like classical swine fever and scrapie are specific to one type of stock, while others, like foot-and-mouth disease affect all cloven-hoofed animals.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animals living under intensive conditions are prone to internal and external parasites; increasing numbers of sea lice are affecting farmed salmon in Scotland.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Reducing the parasite burdens of livestock results in increased productivity and profitability.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Where the condition is serious, governments impose regulations on imports and exports, the movement of stock, quarantine restrictions, and the reporting of suspected cases.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Vaccines are available against certain diseases, and antibiotics are widely used where appropriate.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] At one time, antibiotics were routinely added to certain compound foodstuffs to promote growth.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Still, this practice is now frowned on in many countries because of the risk that it may lead to antimicrobial resistance in livestock and in humans.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Governments are concerned with zoonoses, diseases that humans may acquire from animals.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Wild animal populations may harbour diseases that can affect domestic animals, which may acquire them as a result of insufficient biosecurity.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] An outbreak of Nipah virus in Malaysia in 1999 was traced back to pigs becoming ill after contact with fruit-eating flying foxes, their faeces and urine.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The pigs, in turn, passed the infection to humans.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Avian flu H5N1 is present in wild bird populations and can be carried large distances by migrating birds.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] This virus is easily transmissible to domestic poultry and to humans living in proximity to them.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Other infectious diseases affecting wild animals, farm animals and humans include rabies, leptospirosis, brucellosis, tuberculosis and trichinosis.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] There is no single universally agreed-upon definition of what species are considered livestock.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Widely recognized livestock types include cattle for beef and dairy, sheep, goats, pigs, and poultry.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Various other species are sometimes considered livestock, such as horses, while poultry birds are sometimes excluded.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In some parts of the world, livestock includes species such as buffalo, and the South American camelids, the alpaca and llama.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Some authorities use much broader definitions to include fish in aquaculture, micro-livestock such as rabbits and rodents like guinea pigs, as well as insects from honey bees to crickets raised for human consumption.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animals are raised for a wide variety of products, principally meat, wool, milk, and eggs, but also including tallow, isinglass, and rennet.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animals are also kept for more specialised purposes, such as to produce vaccines and antiserum (containing antibodies) for medical use.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Where fodder or other crops are grown alongside animals, manure can serve as a fertiliser, returning minerals and organic matter to the soil in a semi-closed organic system.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Although all mammals produce milk to nourish their young, cows are predominantly used worldwide to produce milk and milk products for human consumption.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Other animals used to a lesser extent for this purpose include sheep, goats, camels, buffaloes, yaks, reindeer, horses, and donkeys.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] All these animals have been domesticated over the centuries, bred for desirable characteristics such as fecundity, productivity, docility, and the ability to thrive under prevailing conditions.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Whereas in the past cattle had multiple functions, modern dairy cow breeding has produced specialised Holstein Friesian-type animals that produce large quantities of milk economically.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Artificial insemination is widely available, allowing farmers to select for traits that suit their circumstances.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In many communities, milk production is only part of the purpose of keeping an animal, which may also be used as a beast of burden or to draw a plough, or for the production of fibre, meat and leather, with the dung being used for fuel or for the improvement of soil fertility.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Sheep and goats may be favoured for dairy production in climates and conditions that do not suit dairy cows.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Meat, mainly from farmed animals, is a major source of dietary protein and essential nutrients around the world, averaging about 8% of human energy intake.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The actual types eaten depend on local preferences, availability, cost, and other factors, with cattle, sheep, pigs, and goats being the main species involved.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Cattle generally produce a single offspring annually which takes more than a year to mature; sheep and goats often have twins and these are ready for slaughter in less than a year; pigs are more prolific, producing more than one litter of up to about 11 piglets each year.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Horses, donkeys, deer, buffalo, llamas, alpacas, guanacos and vicunas are farmed for meat in various regions.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Some desirable traits of animals raised for meat include fecundity, hardiness, fast growth rate, ease of management, and high food conversion efficiency.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] About half of the world's meat is produced from animals grazing on open ranges or enclosed pastures; the other half is produced intensively in various factory-farming systems.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] These are mostly cows, pigs, or poultry, and are often reared indoors at high densities.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Poultry kept for their eggs and meat include chickens, turkeys, geese, and ducks.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The great majority of laying birds used for egg production are chickens.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The battery cages are arranged in long rows across multiple tiers, with external feeders, drinkers, and egg-collection facilities.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] This is the most labour-saving and economical method of egg production.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Still, it has been criticised on animal-welfare grounds because the birds are unable to exhibit their normal behaviours.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In the developed world, the majority of poultry reared for meat is raised indoors in large sheds, with automated equipment and environmentally controlled conditions.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Chickens raised in this way are known as broilers, and genetic improvements have enabled them to reach slaughter weight within six or seven weeks of hatching.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Newly hatched chicks are confined to a small area and provided with supplementary heating.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Litter on the floor absorbs droppings, and the area it occupies expands as they grow.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Feed and water are supplied automatically, and the lighting is controlled.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The birds may be harvested on several occasions, or the entire shed may be cleared at once.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] A similar rearing system is usually used for turkeys, which are less hardy than chickens, take longer to reach maturity, and are often moved to separate fattening units to finish.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Ducks are particularly popular in Asia and Australia and can be killed at seven weeks under commercial conditions.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Aquaculture has been defined as "the farming of aquatic organisms, including fish, molluscs, crustaceans, and aquatic plants, and implies some form of intervention in the rearing process to enhance production, such as regular stocking, feeding, protection from predators, etc.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Farming also implies individual or corporate ownership of the stock being cultivated." In practice, it can take place in the sea or in freshwater, and be extensive or intensive.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Whole bays, lakes, or ponds may be devoted to aquaculture, or the farmed animal may be retained in cages (fish), artificial reefs, racks, or strings (shellfish).
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Fish and prawns can be cultivated in rice paddies, either arriving naturally or being introduced, and both crops can be harvested together.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Fish hatcheries provide larval and juvenile fish, crustaceans, and shellfish for use in aquaculture systems.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] When large enough, these are transferred to growing-on tanks and sold to fish farms for harvest.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Some species that are commonly raised in hatcheries include shrimps, prawns, salmon, tilapia, oysters and scallops.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Similar facilities can be used to raise species with conservation needs for release into the wild, or game fish for restocking waterways.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Important aspects of husbandry at these early stages include selection of breeding stock, control of water quality, and nutrition.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In the wild, there is a high mortality rate at the nursery stage; farmers seek to minimise it while maximising growth rates.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Bees have been kept in hives since at least the First Dynasty of Egypt, five thousand years ago, and man had been harvesting honey from the wild long before that.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Fixed-comb hives are used in many parts of the world and are made from locally available materials.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In more advanced economies, where modern strains of domestic bee have been selected for docility and productiveness, various designs of hive are used which enable the combs to be removed for processing and extraction of honey.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Quite apart from the honey and wax they produce, honey bees are important pollinators of crops and wild plants, and in many places hives are transported around the countryside to assist in pollination.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Sericulture, the rearing of silkworms, was first adopted by the Chinese during the Shang dynasty.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The only species farmed commercially is the domesticated silkmoth.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] When it spins its cocoon, each larva produces an exceedingly long, slender thread of silk.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The larvae feed on mulberry leaves, and in Europe, only one generation is typically raised each year because mulberry is a deciduous tree.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In China, Korea, and Japan, however, two generations are normal, and in the tropics, multiple generations are expected.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Most silk production occurs in the Far East, with synthetic diets used to rear silkworms in Japan.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Insects form part of the human diet in many cultures.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In Thailand, crickets are farmed for this purpose in the north of the country, and palm weevil larvae in the south.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The crickets are kept in pens, boxes, or drawers and fed on commercial pelleted poultry food, while the palm weevil larvae live on cabbage palm and sago palm trees, which limits their production to areas where these trees grow.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Another delicacy of this region is the bamboo caterpillar, and the best rearing and harvesting techniques in semi-natural habitats are being studied.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animal husbandry has a significant impact on the world environment.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Both production and consumption of animal products have increased rapidly.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Since 1950, meat production has tripled, dairy production has doubled, and egg production has increased almost fourfold.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Meanwhile, meat consumption has nearly doubled worldwide.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Developing countries had a surge in meat consumption, particularly of monogastric livestock.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animal husbandry drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss, and kills 60 billion animals annually.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] It uses between 20 and 33% of the world's fresh water, Livestock, and the production of feed for them, occupy about a third of the Earth's ice-free land.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Livestock production contributes to species extinction, desertification, and habitat destruction. and is the primary driver of the Holocene extinction.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Some 70% of the agricultural land and 30% of Earth's land surface is involved directly or indirectly in animal husbandry.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Habitat is destroyed by clearing forests and converting land to grow feed crops and for grazing, while predators and herbivores are frequently targeted because of a perceived threat to livestock profits; for example, animal husbandry causes up to 91% of the deforestation in the Amazon region.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] In addition, livestock produce greenhouse gases.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Cows produce some 570 million cubic metres of methane per day, that accounts for 35 to 40% of the overall methane emissions of the planet.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Further, livestock production is responsible for 65% of all human-related emissions of nitrous oxide.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Since the 18th century, people have become increasingly concerned about the welfare of farm animals.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Possible measures of welfare include longevity, behavior, physiology, reproduction, freedom from disease, and freedom from immunosuppression.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] An opposing view is that animals have rights, should not be regarded as property, are not necessary to use, and should never be used by humans.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Live export of animals has risen to meet increased global demand for livestock, such as in the Middle East.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Animal rights activists have objected to the long-distance transport of animals; one result was the banning of live exports from New Zealand in 2003.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Since the 18th century, the farmer John Bull has represented English national identity, first in John Arbuthnot's political satires, and soon afterwards in cartoons by James Gillray and others, including John Tenniel.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] He likes food, beer, dogs, horses, and country sports; he is practical, down-to-earth, and anti-intellectual.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Farm animals are widespread in children's books and songs; the reality of animal husbandry is often distorted, softened, or idealized, giving children an almost entirely fictitious account of farm life.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The books often depict happy animals free to roam in attractive countryside, a picture completely at odds with the realities of the impersonal, mechanized activities involved in modern intensive farming.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Pigs, for example, appear in several of Beatrix Potter's "little books", as Piglet in A.A.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Milne's Winnie the Pooh stories, and somewhat more darkly (with a hint of animals going to slaughter) as Babe in Dick King-Smith's *The Sheep-Pig*, and as Wilbur in E.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Pigs tend to be "bearers of cheerfulness, good humour and innocence".
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Many of these books are completely anthropomorphic, dressing farm animals in clothes and having them walk on two legs, live in houses, and perform human activities.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] The children's song "Old MacDonald Had a Farm" describes a farmer named MacDonald and the various animals he keeps, celebrating the noises they each make.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Many urban children experience animal husbandry for the first time at a petting farm; in Britain, some five million people a year visit a farm of some kind.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] This presents some risk of infection, especially if children handle animals and then fail to wash their hands; a strain of *E. coli* infected 93 people who had visited a British interactive farm in an outbreak in 2009.
[src:animal-husbandry/animal-husbandry] Historic farms such as those in the United States offer farmstays and "a carefully curated version of farming to those willing to pay for it", sometimes giving visitors a romanticised image of a pastoral idyll from an unspecified time in the pre-industrial past.
